	"conclusion": "For Notion, the career page partially precedes Linkedin: 22% of matched jobs (10/46) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 119 days (median: 43 days). An additional 106 jobs (70% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Linkedin at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "An analysis of job posting patterns from January 2024 to April 2026 reveals that while LinkedIn often posts jobs concurrently or even slightly before company career pages, a significant advantage exists for roles appearing first on career pages. Out of 46 matched job postings across both platforms, 10 (22%) appeared first on the company's dedicated career page. For these instances, the career page offered a substantial head start, with an average lag of 119 days and a median lag of 43 days before the same position was observed on LinkedIn. This indicates that when a company's own site is the initial publication point, the lead time can be considerable, ranging from a few days to many months.\n\nFurther examination of the lag distribution for these career-page-first jobs highlights a clear pattern: 70% (7 out of 10) of such jobs appeared on career pages at least 15 days earlier than on LinkedIn. Specifically, 20% (2 jobs) were ahead by 1-3 days, another 20% (2 jobs) by 15-30 days, and a further 20% (2 jobs) by 31-60 days. A substantial 30% (3 jobs) exhibited a lag of 90 days or more, giving early applicants a significant competitive edge in roles like \"Account Executive, Mid-Market,\" which appeared 632 days earlier on the career page. This consistent pattern of early publication on company sites provides a distinct window of opportunity for proactive job seekers.\n\nIt is crucial to acknowledge several limitations influencing these findings. The analysis processed 200 career page snapshots but only 6 LinkedIn snapshots over the 27-month period, which likely undercounts the true frequency and earliest appearance dates of jobs on LinkedIn. This disparity in snapshot frequency means that the observed \"LinkedIn first\" instances or \"same day\" appearances might be skewed, and some LinkedIn postings could have appeared earlier than captured. Additionally, 106 unique jobs were identified solely on career pages, never appearing on LinkedIn within the analysis period, suggesting that a significant portion of a company's hiring activity might not be mirrored on external platforms.\n\nGiven these insights, job seekers are strongly recommended to monitor company career pages directly. By doing so, individuals can gain access to job openings many weeks or even months before they might be published on platforms like LinkedIn. Prioritizing direct visits to company career sites for target organizations will provide a competitive advantage, potentially allowing applicants to apply before the broader candidate pool is aware of the opening, particularly for roles exhibiting a median lag of 43 days or more.",
